          "body": "What Psalm 123 models, compressed into four verses, is the complete anatomy of prayer under social suffering. It begins with **orientation** — where the eyes go before the mouth opens (v.1). It proceeds to **posture** — how the eyes look, with the patience and attentiveness of a servant who has no alternative plan (v.2). It moves to **petition** — a doubled, urgent, grace-based request that does not pretend the suffering is less than it is (v.3). It closes with **diagnosis** — the precise naming of the wound, refusing both denial and despair (v.4). There is no resolution in the psalm. No answer is given, no deliverance is announced, no divine speech is recorded. The psalm ends with the soul still full of contempt and the petition still unanswered within the text. This is not a failure of the psalm; it is the psalm's most important pastoral feature. It models what to do while you are waiting for the 'until' of verse 2 to arrive: lift your eyes, watch the hand, ask for grace, and name the pain honestly to the One enthroned above it all."
