        "body": "The movement from simile to petition at verse 3 is swift and deliberate. The psalm has spent two verses establishing the posture (eyes up) and the quality (servant-like attentiveness). Now the mouth opens. The cry is doubled — *chonnenu Yehovah chonnenu* — 'be gracious to us, O LORD, be gracious to us.' In Hebrew poetry, repetition of a request is not rhetorical padding; it is the intensification of urgency and the declaration of sincere need. The doubled imperative signals that the community has been waiting a long time, that the petition has already been prayed, and that it is being prayed again with full weight behind it.\n\nThe verb *chanan* (be gracious) is the psalm's operative term and carries the entire theological logic of the petition. The community does not appeal to its faithfulness, its pilgrimage, its suffering-as-merit, or its religious observance. It appeals to **grace** — unmerited favor from the One in power. This is precisely consistent with the servant-posture of verse 2: a servant cannot demand from a master; a servant can only ask. The petition is calibrated to the analogy. The Psalms that open 'do not deal with us according to our sins' (cf. Psalm 103:10) share the same theological logic: the appeal is always to the character of God, not the record of the petitioner.\n\nThe 'for' (*ki*) that introduces the second half of verse 3 provides the explicit ground of the petition: 'for we are greatly filled with contempt.' This is honest prayer in the tradition of the Psalter's lament literature. God is not being surprised with new information; He is being addressed by a community that insists on speaking plainly about its condition. Derek Kidner (*Psalms 73-150*) notes that the willingness to name the wound explicitly — without softening, theologizing, or spiritualizing it prematurely — is itself a form of faith. The community does not yet know how or when deliverance will come; it knows to whom to bring the unvarnished truth.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chonnenu* — the doubled imperative Qal of *chanan*; the same root appears in the Aaronic blessing ('the LORD be gracious to you,' Numbers 6:25), in Psalm 51:1 ('be gracious to me, O God, according to Your lovingkindness'), and in Psalm 86:3, 6 (doubled petition). *Sava* (greatly filled) — to be satiated, surfeited; the verb used of being full from eating (Proverbs 30:22). The soul is not merely touched by contempt; it is stuffed with it. *Buz* (contempt) — dismissive disdain, the low estimation expressed toward someone regarded as beneath notice."
