        "title": "The anatomy of contempt — the comfortable scoffing at the faithful",
        "range": "123:4",
        "excerpt": "Our soul is greatly filled with the scoffing of those who are at ease, and with the contempt of the proud.",
        "body": "Verse 4 closes the psalm without resolution, without a divine response, and without a change of circumstance — and this is its most important pastoral feature. The final verse simply completes the diagnosis begun in verse 3, naming the source and the character of the suffering with increasing precision. The soul (*nephesh*, the inner person, the seat of identity and feeling) has been saturated — *sava* repeats from verse 3, hammering the point — with two related but distinct forms of social aggression.\n\n*Laag* (scoffing, mocking, jeering) describes the active, verbal expression of contempt: laughter, ridicule, the dismissive joke at the expense of the faithful. *Shaanan* (those at ease) identifies the source: people whose circumstances are comfortable, whose social position is secure, and whose ease has bred the cruelty of the unafflicted toward the afflicted. This is a specific and ancient dynamic. Those who have never needed God mock those who do; those whose prosperity is intact find the desperation of prayer contemptible. *Buz* (contempt) adds the attitudinal dimension — the low estimate, the dismissal, the silent treatment that communicates 'you are beneath serious engagement.' And *gaayon* (the proud) characterizes these people's fundamental orientation: self-exaltation, the refusal to bow to any authority above themselves.\n\nThe pastoral weight of this verse is considerable. The community's suffering is not the suffering of physical persecution, imprisonment, or exile — it is the suffering of being socially mocked by people in better circumstances. Many commentators (Goldingay, *Psalms 90-150*, Baker Commentary on the Old Testament) have noted that this is the specific situation of Jewish diaspora existence: a minority community maintaining costly religious devotion in a world that found it absurd, surrounded by neighbors whose gods demanded less and whose lives seemed easier. The scoffing was continuous, low-level, and corrosive. Psalm 123 does not provide an answer to that scoffing; it provides a direction: keep looking up.\n\nThat the psalm ends with the wound still open is not a failure of the genre. The Psalms of Ascents as a collection move toward confidence and blessing — Psalms 124-134 include strong notes of deliverance and praise. Psalm 123 occupies the lament position within the sequence, and its incompleteness is part of its purpose: to give voice to the community that has not yet received the 'until.' The posture of verse 2 — watching the hand without a deadline — is confirmed by an ending that refuses false resolution. Eyes up; soul full; petition doubled; waiting.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nephesh* (soul, v.4) — the whole inner person, the seat of consciousness and desire; used here rather than *ruach* (spirit) or *lev* (heart) to indicate the totality of the person's inner life being filled. *Laag* (scoffing) — mocking speech, derision; also used in Psalm 22:7 of those who mock the suffering righteous. *Shaanan* (at ease) — settled, undisturbed; used in Amos 6:1 of those 'at ease in Zion' who are blind to coming judgment. *Gaayon* (the proud) — the abstract noun of *gaah* (to be high, to rise); describes those whose self-elevation has become identity."
